Hello Indians, I just watched the movie Dhurandhar. I was curious about what kind of film it would be, so after watching it, I&#39;m writing my review.<br/><br/>(India is like an ex-girlfriend of Pakistan who still hasn&#39;t been able to move on after the breakup.)
If this movie is being called &quot;time-pass&quot; or &quot;entertainment,&quot; then Indians should honestly be ashamed of a mentality that takes a completely fictional story as reality. Rehman Dakaith, who was nothing more than a local gangster from Lyari Town in Karachi, is somehow made responsible for the 26/11 attacks ü§£-and on top of that, an entire nation is shown hating Rehman Dakaith for it üëè.<br/><br/>Maybe in India it&#39;s possible for a street criminal to say this to an intelligence officer: &quot;Rehman Dakait ki di huyi maut badi kasayinuma hoti hai.&quot;
Brother, if anyone said something like that in Pakistan, zabaan se poncha lagwayenge yeh.<br/><br/>We do not wear half-sleeve kameez. There is no gun factory in Lyari Town. I have personally lived in Lyari Town since childhood.<br/><br/>And no-we don&#39;t say &quot;adaab,&quot; brother.<br/><br/>Give Akshaye Khanna an Oscar ü§£ü§£ü§£.<br/><br/>What a hilariously delusional nation ü§£ü§£ü§£.
